06000nam a22009975i 9781847698704DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20132013enk    fo  d z      eng d  a2012036459  a97818476987047 a10.21832/97818476987042doi  a(DE-B1597)491438  a(OCoLC)843079014  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aenkcGB-BST00aP128.I53bN38 2013 4aP 7aEDU0000002bisacsh00aNative-Speakerism in Japan :bIntergroup Dynamics in Foreign Language Education /ced. by Stephanie Ann Houghton, Damian J. Rivers. 1aBristol ;aBlue Ridge Summit : bMultilingual Matters, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMultilingual Matters0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe relative status of native and non-native speaker language teachers within educational institutions has long been an issue worldwide but until recently, the voices of teachers articulating their own concerns have been rare. Existing work has tended to focus upon the position of non-native teachers and their struggle against unfavourable comparisons with their native-speaker counterparts. However, more recently, native-speaker language teachers have also been placed in the academic spotlight as interest grows in language-based forms of prejudice such as ‘native-speakerism’ – a dominant ideology prevalent within the Japanese context of English language education. This innovative volume explores wide-ranging issues related to native-speakerism as it manifests itself in the Japanese and Italian educational contexts to show how native-speaker teachers can also be the targets of multifarious forms of prejudice and discrimination in the workplace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aLanguage and langua